# 🧪 CareerForge AI V2 — Model Training, Evaluation & Validation Strategy

## Complete ML Quality Assurance Blueprint

> **Purpose**: Define EXACTLY what to train, measure, compare, and decide
> **No code, no theory** — only specifications, targets, and decision criteria

---

## 📌 TASK 1 — Data Splitting Strategy

| Split | Percentage | Size (~2,484 total) | Purpose |
|-------|-----------|--------------------|---------| 
| **Training** | 70% | ~1,739 resumes | Model learning |
| **Validation** | 15% | ~373 resumes | Hyperparameter tuning, early stopping |
| **Test** | 15% | ~372 resumes | Final unbiased evaluation |

### Split Requirements

| Requirement | What It Means |
|------------|---------------|
| **Stratified Split** | Each split maintains the same role distribution as the full dataset |
| **No Data Leakage** | Test set is NEVER seen during training or tuning |
| **Reproducible** | Fixed random seed so results are repeatable |
| **Per-Class Balance** | Each of the 25 roles has proportional representation in every split |

### Expected Per-Role Count (Post-Split)

| Role | Training (~70%) | Validation (~15%) | Test (~15%) |
|------|-----------------|-------------------|-------------|
| Each of 25 roles (~96 each) | ~67 | ~14 | ~15 |

---

## 📌 TASK 2 — Train Role Classification Models

### Models to Train

| # | Model | Why This Model |
|---|-------|---------------|
| 1 | **Multinomial Naive Bayes** | Fast text classification baseline; handles sparse TF-IDF well |
| 2 | **Logistic Regression** | Strong linear model; outputs calibrated probabilities |
| 3 | **Random Forest** | Non-linear; captures feature interactions; robust to noise |

### Training Configuration

| Parameter | Specification |
|-----------|--------------|
| **Input** | TF-IDF feature vectors from Module 3 |
| **Labels** | 25 role categories (encoded 0–24) |
| **Training Set** | 70% of dataset (stratified) |
| **Validation** | 15% for hyperparameter tuning |
| **Cross-Validation** | 5-fold stratified on training set |

---

## 📌 TASK 3 — Model Comparison

### Metrics to Compute (for EACH model)

| Metric | What It Measures | Target |
|--------|-----------------|--------|
| **Accuracy** | Overall correct predictions / total | ≥ 85% |
| **Precision** (macro) | Avg precision across all 25 classes | ≥ 80% |
| **Recall** (macro) | Avg recall across all 25 classes | ≥ 80% |
| **F1-Score** (macro) | Harmonic mean of precision & recall | ≥ 80% |
| **F1-Score** (weighted) | Class-size weighted F1 | ≥ 85% |

### Comparison Table Template

| Model | Accuracy | Precision | Recall | F1 (macro) | F1 (weighted) | Training Time |
|-------|----------|-----------|--------|------------|---------------|---------------|
| Naive Bayes | ? | ? | ? | ? | ? | ? |
| Logistic Regression | ? | ? | ? | ? | ? | ? |
| Random Forest | ? | ? | ? | ? | ? | ? |

### Decision Rule

```
IF F1(weighted) difference < 2% between models:
  → SELECT the one with better macro F1 (handles minority classes better)
ELSE:
  → SELECT the one with highest F1(weighted)

TIE-BREAKER: Faster training time wins
```

---

## 📌 TASK 4 — Confusion Matrix Analysis

### What to Analyze

| Analysis | What to Look For |
|----------|-----------------|
| **Highly Confused Pairs** | Which two roles get misclassified as each other most often? |
| **Weak Classes** | Roles with precision OR recall below 70% |
| **Strong Classes** | Roles with F1 > 90% (easiest to classify) |
| **Asymmetric Confusion** | Role A misclassified as B, but NOT B as A |

### Expected Problem Areas

| Potentially Confused Roles | Reason |
|---------------------------|--------|
| HR ↔ BPO | Overlapping organizational/people skills |
| Sales ↔ Business-Development | Similar business vocabulary |
| Finance ↔ Banking ↔ Accountant | Shared financial domain language |
| Engineering ↔ Information-Technology | Overlapping technical skills |
| Designer ↔ Digital-Media | Creative domain overlap |

### Decision Matrix

| Finding | Action |
|---------|--------|
| Two roles confused > 20% of the time | Consider merging labels OR adding distinguishing features |
| A role has recall < 60% | Investigate if the role has too few distinctive features |
| A role has precision < 60% | Other roles are being falsely labeled as this role — add negative features |
| Overall accuracy < 80% | Re-evaluate feature extraction (M3) — try different TF-IDF settings |

---

## 📌 TASK 5 — Skill Extraction Validation

### Validation Method

| Test | How to Validate | Pass Condition |
|------|----------------|----------------|
| **Coverage Test** | Manually review 20 resumes — are all visible skills extracted? | ≥ 80% of human-identified skills found |
| **Precision Test** | Are extracted skills actually valid skills? | ≤ 10% false positives |
| **Categorization Test** | Are skills placed in the correct category? | ≥ 85% correct categorization |
| **Edge Cases** | Abbreviated skills (ML, NLP, JS), multi-word skills (Machine Learning) | All common abbreviations handled |

### Validation Checklist

| Check | Status |
|-------|--------|
| Extracts multi-word skills (e.g., "Machine Learning") | ☐ |
| Handles abbreviations (e.g., "NLP" → "Natural Language Processing") | ☐ |
| Differentiates Technical vs. Soft skills correctly | ☐ |
| Doesn't extract random words as skills | ☐ |
| Works on resumes from all 25 role categories | ☐ |

### Decision

| Finding | Action |
|---------|--------|
| Missing > 20% of skills | Expand skill recognition patterns |
| Too many false positives | Tighten extraction rules / improve filtering |
| Category errors > 15% | Retrain/improve categorization logic |

---

## 📌 TASK 6 — Scoring Model Validation

### Consistency Checks

| Test Case | Expected Outcome |
|-----------|-----------------|
| Resume with 20+ relevant skills, clear experience | Score > 75 |
| Resume with 5–10 skills, moderate experience | Score 40–75 |
| Resume with < 5 skills, no clear experience | Score < 40 |
| Two similar resumes (same role, similar skills) | Scores within ±10 points |
| Adding a relevant skill to a resume | Score increases |
| Resume with skills mismatching predicted role | Lower score than matched resume |

### Distribution Checks

| Check | Expected |
|-------|----------|
| Score distribution shape | Roughly normal (bell curve centered around 50–60) |
| No scores at exactly 0 or exactly 100 | No extreme edge cases |
| Score spread per role | Each role category has a score range, not a single value |
| Percentile distribution | 25th/50th/75th percentiles are meaningful and distinct |

### Decision Matrix

| Finding | Action |
|---------|--------|
| All scores cluster in narrow range (±15) | Increase scoring sensitivity; adjust dimension weights |
| High-quality resumes scoring < 50 | Increase weight of valid positive signals |
| Low-quality resumes scoring > 70 | Add penalties for missing components |
| Scores not correlated with skill count | Skill relevance weight too low — increase it |

---

## 📌 TASK 7 — Risk Model Validation

### Consistency Checks

| Test Case | Expected Outcome |
|-----------|-----------------|
| Resume with score > 80 | Risk: Low (< 30%) |
| Resume with score 40–60 | Risk: Medium (30–60%) |
| Resume with score < 40 | Risk: High (> 60%) |
| Resume with many skills but wrong role | Risk: Medium (misalignment) |
| Resume with few skills in any role | Risk: High |

### Inverse Correlation Check

| Validation | Expected |
|-----------|----------|
| Score vs. Risk correlation | Strong negative correlation (r < −0.7) |
| High score → Low risk | Consistent across all 25 role categories |
| Risk factors match score weaknesses | Same dimensions that drag score down should appear as risk factors |

### Decision Matrix

| Finding | Action |
|---------|--------|
| Risk doesn't inversely correlate with score | Re-calibrate risk thresholds |
| Same resumes get "High Risk" and "High Score" | Conflicting logic — fix the scoring or risk model |
| Risk factors are too generic | Make risk explanations more specific to the resume |
| All resumes get "Medium Risk" | Threshold ranges too tight — expand Low/High bands |

---

## 📌 TASK 8 — Matching Engine Evaluation

### Test Scenarios

| Scenario | Expected Match % |
|----------|-----------------|
| IT resume matched with IT job description | > 70% |
| IT resume matched with Chef job description | < 30% |
| Finance resume matched with Banking JD | 50–80% (related but different) |
| Resume with exact skills mentioned in JD | > 85% |
| Resume with zero skill overlap | < 15% |

### Quality Checks

| Check | Pass Condition |
|-------|---------------|
| Relevant resumes rank higher than irrelevant | Top-5 candidates for a JD should be from matching roles |
| Match % correlates with skill overlap | Higher skill overlap → higher match % |
| Semantic similarity captures meaning | "Software Engineer" and "Developer" are matched as similar |
| Non-matching resumes get low scores | No irrelevant resume gets > 50% match |

---

## 📌 TASK 9 — Overfitting Detection

### Comparison Table

| Metric | Training Set | Validation Set | Test Set | Status |
|--------|-------------|---------------|----------|--------|
| Accuracy | ? | ? | ? | ? |
| F1 (macro) | ? | ? | ? | ? |
| F1 (weighted) | ? | ? | ? | ? |

### Overfitting Rules

| Condition | Diagnosis | Action |
|-----------|-----------|--------|
| Train acc − Val acc > 10% | **Overfitting** | Simplify model / add regularization / reduce features |
| Train acc − Val acc > 5% | **Mild overfitting** | Monitor; consider regularization |
| Train acc − Val acc < 5% | **Good fit** | Acceptable |
| Val acc > Train acc | **Unusual** | Check for data leakage — this shouldn't happen |
| Test acc ≈ Val acc (±3%) | **Generalization confirmed** | Model is ready |
| Test acc << Val acc (>5% drop) | **Selection bias** | Re-split data and retrain |

---

## 📌 TASK 10 — Final Model Selection

### Selection Criteria (Weighted)

| Criterion | Weight | Decision Factor |
|-----------|--------|----------------|
| **Test F1 (weighted)** | 35% | Primary performance metric |
| **Test F1 (macro)** | 25% | Performance on minority classes |
| **No overfitting** | 20% | Train-test gap < 5% |
| **Inference speed** | 10% | < 500ms per prediction |
| **Interpretability** | 10% | Feature importance available for XAI |

### Final Decision Template

| Decision | Selected |
|----------|---------|
| **Role Classification Model** | [Best of NB/LR/RF] |
| **Scoring Logic** | [Weighted dimension formula — final weights] |
| **Risk Thresholds** | Low: [0–X%] / Medium: [X–Y%] / High: [Y–100%] |
| **Matching Method** | [Embedding similarity + skill overlap] |

